State Elections In Israel
This is the first important election in this war-torn country since 2005.
More than 14,400 people entered the race for 440 seats in the state elections.
To maintain peace and safety during the elections, 800,000 police and soldiers were posted in Iraq.
All Iraqi borders were sealed one day in advance fearing that a random bomb blast or terrorist attack might occur on this important day, especially Friday.
Also, airports were closed and restrictions were placed on public transportation.
According to reports, due to the restrictions on public transportation, there was no traffic on Baghdad roads and children were spotted playing football there.
During the present Iraqi elections, security arrangements will reveal whether the local security agencies will be able to control the country after the return of American forces in 2011. Political analysts also are using this as a test to see how far the public is willing to go to bring about democratic change.
The state elections are being overseen by the United Nations and nearly 800 international supervisors.
